{"title_page": "AMSDOS", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2007}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name                   = AMSDOS\n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| developer              = [[Amstrad]] \n| source_model           = [[Closed source]]\n| kernel_type            = \n| supported_platforms    = \n| ui                     = None, access through BASIC and firmware calls\n| family                 = [[Disk operating system]]s\n| released               = {{Start date and age|1984}}\n| latest_release_version = \n| latest_release_date    = \n| latest_test_version    = \n| latest_test_date       = \n| marketing_target       = \n| programmed_in          = \n| prog_language          = [[Locomotive BASIC]]\n| language               = \n| updatemodel            = \n| package_manager        = \n| working_state          = Discontinued\n| license                = \n| website                = \n}}\n'''AMSDOS''' is a [[disk operating system]] for the [[8-bit]] [[Amstrad]] [[Amstrad CPC|CPC Computer]] (and various clones). The name is a contraction of '''Ams'''trad '''D'''isk\n'''O'''perating '''S'''ystem.<ref name=\"CPC 464 Specs\">http://www.old-computers.com/museum/computer.asp?c=84</ref>\n\nAMSDOS first appeared in 1984 on the '''CPC 464''', with added [[Floppy disk|3 inch disk]] drive, and then on the '''CPC 664''' and '''CPC 6128'''. Relatively fast and efficient for its time, AMSDOS was quicker and more effective than most of its contemporaries.\n\nAMSDOS was provided built into ROM (either supplied with the external disk drive or in the machine ROM, depending on model) and was accessible through the built-in [[Locomotive BASIC]] as well as through [[firmware]] routines. Its main function was to map the [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] access routines (which were built into every CPC model) through to a disk drive. This enabled the majority of cassette-based programs to work with a disk drive with no modification. AMSDOS was able to support up to two connected disk drives.\n\n==Commands==\nAMDOS extends the AMSTRAD BASIC by the addition of a number of external [[command (computing)|commands]] which are identified by a preceding [[Vertical bar|<nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki> (bar) symbol]]. The following is a list of external commands supported by AMSDOS.<ref>[http://www.cpcmania.com/Docs/Manuals/CPC664%20User%20Instructions.pdf AMSTRAD CPC664 User Instructions]</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=9em}}\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>A\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>B\n* [[CP/M|<nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>CPM]]\n* [[dir (command)|<nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>DIR]]\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>DISC\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>DISC.IN\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>DISC.OUT\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>DRIVE\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>ERA\n* [[ren (command)|<nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>REN]]\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>TAPE\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>TAPE.IN\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>TAPE.OUT\n* <nowiki>\u00a6</nowiki>USER\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Alternatives==\nOther disk operating systems for the Amstrad range included [[CP/M]] (which was also bundled with an external disk drive, or built-in on ROM depending on model), RAMDOS, which allowed the full (800K) capacity of single-density 3 \u00bd\" disks to be used providing a suitable drive was connected and [[SymbOS]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Operating system}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amsdos}}\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC]]\n[[Category:Disk operating systems]]\n[[Category:1984 software]]\n\n{{operating-system-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2007}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name                   = AMSDOS\n| logo                   = \n| screenshot             = \n| caption                = \n| developer              = [[Amstrad]] \n| source_model           = [[Closed source]]\n| kernel_type            = \n| supported_platforms    = \n| ui                     = None, access through BASIC and firmware calls\n| family                 = [[Disk operating system]]s\n| released               = {{Start date and age|1984}}\n| latest_release_version = \n| latest_release_date    = \n| latest_test_version    = \n| latest_test_date       = \n| marketing_target       = \n| programmed_in          = \n| prog_language          = [[Locomotive BASIC]]\n| language               = \n| updatemodel            = \n| package_manager        = \n| working_state          = Discontinued\n| license                = \n| website                = \n}}\n'''AMSDOS''' is a [[disk operating system]] for the [[8-bit]] [[Amstrad]] [[Amstrad CPC|CPC Computer]] (and various clones). The name is a contraction of '''Ams'''trad '''D'''isk\n'''O'''perating '''S'''ystem.<ref name=\"CPC 464 Specs\">http://www.old-computers.com/museum/computer.asp?c=84</ref>\n\nAMSDOS first appeared in 1984 on the '''CPC 464''', with added [[Floppy disk|3 inch disk]] drive, and then on the '''CPC 664''' and '''CPC 6128'''. Relatively fast and efficient for its time, AMSDOS was quicker and more effective than most of its contemporaries.\n\nAMSDOS was provided built into ROM (either supplied with the external disk drive or in the machine ROM, depending on model) and was accessible through the built-in [[Locomotive BASIC]] as well as through [[firmware]] routines. Its main function was to map the [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] access routines (which were built into every CPC model) through to a disk drive. This enabled the majority of cassette-based programs to work with a disk drive with no modification. AMSDOS was able to support up to two connected disk drives.\n\n==Commands==\nAMDOS extends the AMSTRAD BASIC by the addition of a number of external [[command (computing)|commands]] which are identified by a preceding [[Vertical bar|<nowiki>|</nowiki> (bar) symbol]]. The following is a list of external commands supported by AMSDOS.<ref>[http://www.cpcmania.com/Docs/Manuals/CPC664%20User%20Instructions.pdf AMSTRAD CPC664 User Instructions]</ref>\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=9em}}\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>A\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>B\n* [[CP/M|<nowiki>|</nowiki>CPM]]\n* [[dir (command)|<nowiki>|</nowiki>DIR]]\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>DISC\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>DISC.IN\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>DISC.OUT\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>DRIVE\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>ERA\n* [[ren (command)|<nowiki>|</nowiki>REN]]\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>TAPE\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>TAPE.IN\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>TAPE.OUT\n* <nowiki>|</nowiki>USER\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Alternatives==\nOther disk operating systems for the Amstrad range included [[CP/M]] (which was also bundled with an external disk drive, or built-in on ROM depending on model), RAMDOS, which allowed the full (800K) capacity of single-density 3 \u00bd\" disks to be used providing a suitable drive was connected and [[SymbOS]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Operating system}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amsdos}}\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC]]\n[[Category:Disk operating systems]]\n[[Category:1984 software]]\n\n{{operating-system-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sinewalker", "label": "safe", "comment": "Switched pipe character for vertical bar \u00a6", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AMSDOS"}
