019|accessdate=February 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729005307/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/tom-cruise-mission-impossible-movies-2021-2022-1203126749/|archive-date=July 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| Summer 2022 || ''Jersey Crabs'' || co-production with [[Paramount Animation]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Giardina|first1=Carolyn|title='Spice Girls' Movie in the Works as Paramount Unveils Animation Slate (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/paramount-plans-spice-girls-movie-as-part-newly-unveiled-animation-slate-1217519|date=June 12, 2019|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612145051/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/paramount-plans-spice-girls-movie-as-part-newly-unveiled-animation-slate-1217519|archive-date=June 12, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | TBA ||''[[The Tomorrow War]]''|| co-production with [[Skydance Media]], [[David S. Goyer|Phantom Four Films]] and [[Madhouse (company)|Madhouse Entertainment]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091228012257/http://www.paramount.com/studio/library/complete-library Paramount Pictures Complete Library]\n* {{IMDb company|id=0023400}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Paramount Pictures films| 2020\u20132029]]\n[[Category:2020s in American cinema|Paramount Pictures]]\n[[Category:Lists of 2020s films|Paramount Pictures]]\n{{Paramount Pictures films}}\n", "name_user": "49.146.46.219", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eUpcoming)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Paramount_Pictures_films_(2020%E2%80%932029)"}
{"title_page": "Sirindhorn", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates |date = September 2011}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Sirindhorn\n| image = ITU Telecom World 2016 \u2013 VVIP Tour (30938750506) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Princess Sirindhorn in 2016\n| succession = \n| reign =\n| coronation =\n| predecessor =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|4|2|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Amphorn Sathan Residential Hall]]<br> [[Dusit Palace]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| house = [[:Category:House of Mahidol|Mahidol]] ([[Chakri dynasty]])\n| father      = [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]] (Rama IX)\n| mother = [[Sirikit|Sirikit Kitiyakara]]\n| religion = [[Buddhism]]\n| signature = Signature of sirindhorn.svg\n}}\n{{Thai Royal Family}}\n\n'''Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn''' ({{lang-th|\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e23\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e34\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23}}, {{IPA-th|m\u0101.h\u01ce\u02d0 t\u0361\u0255\u00e0k.kr\u012b\u02d0 s\u00ec.r\u012bn.t\u02b0\u0254\u0304\u02d0n}}; {{RTGS|''Maha Chakkri Sirinthon''}}; born 2 April 1955), formerly '''Princess Sirindhorn Debaratanasuda Kitivadhanadulsobhak''' ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e25\u0e39\u0e01\u0e40\u0e18\u0e2d \u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e34\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e32 \u0e01\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e27\u0e31\u0e12\u0e19\u0e32\u0e14\u0e38\u0e25\u0e42\u0e2a\u0e20\u0e32\u0e04\u0e22\u0e4c}}; {{RTGS|''Sirinthontheppharattanasuda Kitiwatthanadunlasophak''}}), is the second daughter of King [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]].<ref>\"[http://www.kanchanapisek.or.th/biography/sirindhorn/index.en.html Biography of Her Royal Highness Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn]\"</ref>{{efn|*From  5 December 1977 to 5 May 2019, her full ceremonial title was '''Somdech Phra Debaratanarajasuda Chao Fa Maha Chakri Sirindhorn Rathasimagunakornpiyajat Sayamboromrajakumari'''<ref name=\"sirindhornnet\">{{cite web |url = http://www.sirindhorn.net/HRH-biography.en.php |title = Her Royal Highness Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn's Activities |accessdate = February 23, 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160314204901/http://www.sirindhorn.net/HRH-biography.en.php |archive-date = March 14, 2016 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e32 \u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e23\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e34\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23 \u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e2a\u0e35\u0e21\u0e32\u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e22\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e15\u0e34 \u0e2a\u0e22\u0e32\u0e21\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e21\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e01\u0e38\u0e21\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35}}; {{RTGS|''Somdet Phra Theppharat Rat Suda Chao Fa Maha Chakkri Sirinthon Ratthasima Khunakon Piyachat Sayam Borommaratchakumari''}}).<br/>\n\nAfter [[Coronation of Vajiralongkorn|Vajiralongkorn]]'s coronation, Sirindhorn was invested of the title '''Somdech Phra Kanishthadhiraj Chao Krom Somdech Phra Debaratnarajsuda Chao Fa Maha Chakri Sirindhorn Maha Vajiralongkorn Vorarajbhakti Sirikitchakarinibirayabadhana Rathasimagunakornpiyajat Sayamboromrajakumari''' ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e01\u0e19\u0e34\u0e29\u0e10\u0e32\u0e18\u0e34\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e21\u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14\u0e32 \u0e40\u0e08\u0e49\u0e32\u0e1f\u0e49\u0e32\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e23\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e34\u0e19\u0e18\u0e23 \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e32\u0e25\u0e07\u0e01\u0e23\u0e13\u0e27\u0e23\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e20\u0e31\u0e01\u0e14\u0e35 \u0e2a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e34\u0e01\u0e34\u0e08\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e34\u0e13\u0e35\u0e1e\u0e35\u0e23\u0e22\u0e1e\u0e31\u0e12\u0e19 \u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e2a\u0e35\u0e21\u0e32\u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e22\u0e0a\u0e32\u0e15\u0e34 \u0e2a\u0e22\u0e32\u0e21\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e21\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e01\u0e38\u0e21\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35}}; {{RTGS|''Somdet Phra Kanitthathirat Chao Krom Somdet Phra Theppharat Rat Suda Chao Fa Maha Chakkri Sirinthon Maha Wachiralongkon Woraratchaphakdi Siri Kitcha Karini Phirayaphat Ratthasima Khunakon Piyachat Sayam Borommaratchakumari''}}). }}\n\nThais commonly refer to her as \"Phra Thep\" ({{lang-th|\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e}}), meaning \"princess angel\". Her title in Thai is the female equivalent of the title once held by her brother, [[Monarchy of Thailand|King]] Maha [[Vajiralongkorn]].<ref>Backman, Michael, \"[http://www.theage.com.au/news/business/thai-riches-hinged-on-wise-kings-prodigal-son/2006/06/27/1151174201241.html?page=2 Thai riches hinged on wise king's prodigal son]\" ''The Age'', 28 June 2006.</ref> The Thai constitution was altered in 1974 to allow for female succession, thus making her eligible for the throne.<ref>{{Citation |first = Roger |last = Kershaw |title = Monarchy in South East Asia: The faces of tradition in transition |publisher = Routledge |year = 2001 |page = 153}}</ref>\n\nHaving been the eldest female child of the royal family (excluding [[Ubol Ratana|Princess Ubolratana Rajakanya]], who married a foreign commoner), her position is comparable to a [[Princess Royal|princess royal]].<ref>{{Citation |first = Duncan |last = McCargo |title = Thailand |work = Regional Oulook: Southeast Asia 2010-2011 |publisher = Institute of Southeast Asian Studies |year = 2010 |page = 55 }}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n=== Birth ===\nSirindhorn was born on 2 April 1955 at [[Amphorn Sathan Residential Hall]], [[Dusit Palace]]. The third child of King Bhumibol and Queen [[Sirikit]]. As the royal couple has only one son, the Thai constitution was altered in 1974 to allow for female succession. This made Sirindhorn second-in-line to the throne (after Vajiralongkorn) until the birth of Princess [[Bajrakitiyabha]] in 1978.\n\nIn December 2012, Sirindhorn was briefly hospitalised to remove calcium deposits.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.bangkokpost.com/breakingnews/328136/princess-leaves-hospital |title = Princess Sirindhorn leaves hospital|date = 2012-12-27 |work = [[Bangkok Post]] |accessdate = 20 Sep 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Early education ===\n[[File:Princess sirinhorn 01.jpg|thumb|Princess working]]\nSirindhorn attended Kindergarten, Primary and Secondary at Thailand's most exclusive school: The [[Chitralada School]] which was established for the children of the Royal Family and Palace staff.<ref name=\"EE\">Sut.ac, [http://www.sut.ac.th/radioSUT/HRHsirindh.htm education information] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304092806/http://www.sut.ac.th/radioSUT/HRHsirindh.htm |date=March 4, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nShe ranked first in the National School Examinations in primary level (grade 7) in 1967, in upper secondary level (grade 12) in 1972, and fourth in the [[National Higher Education Entrance Examination|National University Entrance Examination]] in 1975.<ref name=\"EEF\">Pattayamail, [http://www.pattayamail.com/localnews/a-most-happy-birthday-to-her-royal-highness-princess-maha-chakri-sirindhorn-36213 more education information]</ref>\n\n=== Higher education ===\nIn 1975 she enrolled in the faculty of arts at [[Chulalongkorn University]] and graduated with a Bachelor of Arts, first-class honours and a gold medal in history in 1976.<ref name=\"EEF\" />\n\nFrom 1976 she continued her studies in two graduate programs concurrently, obtaining a Master of Arts in [[Epigraphy|Oriental epigraphy]] ([[Sanskrit]] and [[Cambodian language|Cambodian]]) in 1980<ref name=\"EEF\" /> and also [[archaeology]] from [[Silpakorn University]] and in 1980. From October 1977, she studied Sanskrit in Bangkok for two years under the tutelage of renowned Sanskrit scholar [[Satya Vrat Shastri]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wiriyapong|first1=Nareerat|title=Scholar for life|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/1343243/scholar-for-life|accessdate=17 October 2017|work=Bangkok Post|date=16 October 2017}}</ref> In 1978, she obtained a Master of Arts in [[Pali]] and [[Sanskrit]] from [[Chulalongkorn University]].<ref name=\"EE\" />\n\nIn 1981 she enrolled in a doctoral program at [[Srinakharinwirot University]], and was awarded a [[PhD]] in developmental education in 1987.\n\nIn 1984 she earned a certificate from the Asian Regional Remote Sensing Training Centre at the [[Asian Institute of Technology]] where she studied for two months.<ref name=\"AIT\">Asian Institute of Technology, [http://www.ait.ac.th/news-and-events/archive/2006/News.2007-09-12.104134-4/#.ViFc-9m9Kc1 degree information]</ref>\n\nIn April 2001 she won a scholarship in [[Chinese culture]] at [[Peking University]] in China where she studied the course for a month.<ref name=\"PKU\">[[Peking University]], [http://english.pku.edu.cn/News_Events/News/Global/9260.htm scholarship and award information] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202759/http://english.pku.edu.cn/News_Events/News/Global/9260.htm |date=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Works and interests ==\n[[File:\u0e19\u0e32\u0e22\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e10\u0e21\u0e19\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35 \u0e01\u0e23\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e1a\u0e31\u0e07\u0e04\u0e25\u0e17\u0e39\u0e25\u0e23\u0e32\u0e22\u0e07\u0e32\u0e19 \u0e2a\u0e21\u0e40\u0e14\u0e47\u0e08\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e30\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e31\u0e15\u0e19\u0e23\u0e32\u0e0a\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14 - Flickr - Abhisit Vejjajiva.jpg|thumb|right|Princess Sirindhorn in 2011]]\nAside from her passion for technology, she holds degrees in history and a doctorate in educational development. She teaches at the history department of the [[Chulachomklao Royal Military Academy]], where she is the nominal head of the department. In addition to [[Thai language|Thai]], she speaks fluent English, French and Mandarin Chinese, and is currently studying German and [[Latin]]. She translates Chinese literature into Thai.<ref>http://www.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Plush/Story/A1Story20130401-412771.html</ref>\n\nShe is also a skilled performer and avid promoter of Thai traditional music.\n\nLike her father [[Bhumibol Adulyadej]], Princess Sirindhorn holds radio amateur with the [[call sign]] HS1D.<ref>http://www.dx-qsl.com/famous-ham-radio-operators.html</ref>\n\n== Scholarship ==\nThe [[University of Liverpool]] introduced a prestigious new scholarship in honour of Sirindhorn. One full scholarship will be awarded annually to enable a Thai student to study at [[Liverpool]] to complete a one-year taught Masters programme. The scholarship is open to all subjects in which a one-year taught Masters programme is offered; however, priority will be given to those students who wish to study in a subject area associated with Princess Sirindhorn such as science, information technology, medicine, [[the arts]], [[geography]], history, and [[languages]]. To be eligible for the scholarship, applicants must be a [[Thai people|Thai]] national and already hold an offer to study a one-year taught Masters programme at the [[University of Liverpool]].\n\n== Titles, styles, honours and awards ==\n{{Infobox manner of address\n|background = #ba55d3\n|color = #ffffff\n|name = Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn of Thailand\n|image = Standard of HRH Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn (since 5 May 2019).svg\n|size = 180px\n|reference = [[Royal Highness|Her Royal Highness]]\n|spoken = Your Royal Highness\n}}\n\n[[File:Royal Monogram of Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn.svg|thumb|100px|Royal cypher|Royal monogram]]\n\n[[File:Royal Flag of Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn.svg|thumb|160px|Royal flags of Thailand|Royal Cypher Flag]]\n\n=== Titles ===\n* 2 April 1955 \u2013 5 December 1977: ''Her Royal Highness'' Princess Sirindhorn Debaratanasuda\n* 5 December 1977 - present: ''Her Royal Highness'' Princess Maha Chakri Sirindhorn, the Princess Royal of Thailand\n** 5 December 1977 \u2013 5 May 2019: ''Somdech Phra Debaratanarajasuda Chao Fa Maha Chakri Sirindhorn Rathasimagunakarapiyajati Sayam Boromrajakumari''\n** 5 May 2019 \u2013 present: ''Somdech Phra Kanishthadhiraj Chao Krom Somdech Phra Debaratanarajasuda Chao Fa Maha Chakri Sirindhorn Maha Vajiralongkorn Vararajabhakti Sirikicakarini Biryabadhana Rathasimagunakarapiyajati Sayam Boromrajakumari''\n\n===Military rank===\n* [[General]], [[Admiral]] and [[Air Chief Marshal]]<ref>http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2539/B/006/1.PDF</ref>\n\n===Volunteer Defense Corps of Thailand rank===\n* [[Volunteer Defense Corps (Thailand)|Volunteer Defense Corps General]]<ref>http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2535/D/055/1.PDF</ref>\n\n===Academic rank===\n* Professor of [[Chulachomklao Royal Military Academy]]<ref>http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2529/D/103/1.PDF</ref><ref>http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2543/D/082/12.PDF</ref>\n* Professor of [[Srinakharinwirot University]]<ref>http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2534/D/050/2593.PDF</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n====National honours====\n* {{Flag|Thailand}}: Knight Grand Cordon with Chain of the [[Order of the Royal House of Chakri]]<ref>https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/736x/e0/6c/e7/e06ce7923a24dc0b9789d896bb002807.jpg</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://commons.m.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Princess_Sirindhorn_2009-12-7_Royal_Thai_Government_House_4.jpg |title = File:Princess Sirindhorn 2009-12-7 Royal Thai Government House 4.jpg |publisher = |accessdate = February 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = https://commons.m.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Princess_Sirindhorn_2009-12-7_Royal_Thai_Government_House_3.jpg |title = File:Princess Sirindhorn 2009-12-7 Royal Thai Government House 3.jpg |publisher = |accessdate = February 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>http://www.cs.ait.ac.th/wutt/pthep/Img/pratep2.jpg</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = h