{"title_page": "Nancy Hirschmann", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}\n\n'''Nancy Hirschmann''' (born April 25, 1956) is a Professor of Politics  at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]; her specialties are the history of political thought, analytical philosophy, feminist theory, disability theory, and the intersection of political theory and public policy.\n\nShe received an  BA from [[Smith College]] and   MA and PhD degrees  from the [[Johns Hopkins University]]. She then became a member of the [[Cornell University]] faculty  for 12 years before  moving to the University of Pennsylvania  as   Graduate Chair in the Political Science department. She has taught courses on modern political thought, political theory and public policy, feminist political thought, gender and political theory, and contemporary political thought.\n\nHer most recent research is on the topic of disability in [[political theory]].\n\n== Books ==\n\n*''The Subject of Liberty: Toward a Feminist Theory of Freedom.'' 2012. [[Princeton University Press]]. Winner of  the [[Victoria Schuck Award]] for the best book in Women and Politics\n*''Feminist Interpretations of Thomas Hobbes'', co-edited with Joanne Wright. 2013. [[Pennsylvania State University Press]].\n*''Gender, Class, and Freedom in Modern Political Theory.'' 2007. [[Princeton University Press]].\n*''Feminist Interpretations of John Locke'', co-edited with Kirstie M. McClure. 2007. [[Pennsylvania State University Press]].\n*''The Subject of Liberty: Toward A Feminist Theory of Freedom.'' 2003. [[Princeton University Press]].\n*''Women and Welfare: Theory and Practice in the United States and Europe'', co-edited with Ulrike Lieber. 2001. [[Rutgers University Press]].\n*''Revisioning the Political: Feminist Reconstructions of Traditional Concepts in Western Political Theory'', co-edited with Christine Di Stefano. 1996. [[Westview Press]].\n*''Rethinking Obligation: A Feminist Method for Political Theory.'' 1992. [[Cornell University Press]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sas.upenn.edu/polisci/people/standing-faculty/nancy-hirschmann University of Pennsylvania Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hirschmann, Nancy}}\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n\n{{prof-stub}}\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=May 2017}}\n\n'''Nancy Hirschmann''' (born April 25, 1956) is a Professor of Politics  at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]; her specialties are the history of political thought, analytical philosophy, feminist theory, disability theory, and the intersection of political theory and public policy.\n\nShe received an  BA from [[Smith College]] and   MA and PhD degrees  from the [[Johns Hopkins University]]. She then became a member of the [[Cornell University]] faculty  for 12 years before  moving to the University of Pennsylvania  as   Graduate Chair in the Political Science department. She has taught courses on modern political thought, political theory and public policy, feminist political thought, gender and political theory, and contemporary political thought.\n\nHer most recent research is on the topic of disability in [[political theory]].\n\n== Books ==\n\n*''The Subject of Liberty: Toward a Feminist Theory of Freedom.'' 2012. [[Princeton University Press]]. Winner of  the [[Victoria Schuck#Victoria Schuck Award|Victoria Schuck Award]] for the best book in Women and Politics\n*''Feminist Interpretations of Thomas Hobbes'', co-edited with Joanne Wright. 2013. [[Pennsylvania State University Press]].\n*''Gender, Class, and Freedom in Modern Political Theory.'' 2007. [[Princeton University Press]].\n*''Feminist Interpretations of John Locke'', co-edited with Kirstie M. McClure. 2007. [[Pennsylvania State University Press]].\n*''The Subject of Liberty: Toward A Feminist Theory of Freedom.'' 2003. [[Princeton University Press]].\n*''Women and Welfare: Theory and Practice in the United States and Europe'', co-edited with Ulrike Lieber. 2001. [[Rutgers University Press]].\n*''Revisioning the Political: Feminist Reconstructions of Traditional Concepts in Western Political Theory'', co-edited with Christine Di Stefano. 1996. [[Westview Press]].\n*''Rethinking Obligation: A Feminist Method for Political Theory.'' 1992. [[Cornell University Press]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sas.upenn.edu/polisci/people/standing-faculty/nancy-hirschmann University of Pennsylvania Profile]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hirschmann, Nancy}}\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n\n{{prof-stub}}\n{{US-polisci-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nancy_Hirschmann"}
{"title_page": "Alex Pettit", "text_new": "{{BLP unsourced|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| name = Alex Pettit\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = April 3, 1966\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = [[Chief Information Officer]] of the [[State of Oklahoma]]\n| governor = [[Brad Henry]]<br>[[Mary Fallin]]\n| term_start = April 5, 2010\n| term_end = January 3, 2014\n| predecessor = Post created\n| successor = \n| office2 = [[Chief Information Officer]] of the [[Government of Oregon|State of Oregon]]\n| governor2 = [[John Kitzhaber]]<br>[[Kate Brown]]\n| term_start2 = January 4, 2014\n| term_end2 = April 6, 2018\n| predecessor2 =\n| successo2r = \n| occupation = [[Public administration|Public administrator]]\n| party =\n| religion = \n| website =\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Alex Pettit''' is an [[United States|American]] [[public administration]] official who was the [[Chief Information Officer]] for the [[Government of Oregon|State of Oregon]]. As State CIO, Pettit worked in the [[Oregon Department of Administrative Services|Department of Administrative Services]] and was responsible for all information and telecommunication systems for all state agencies.  In March 2014, Pettit was appointed interim CIO for [[Cover Oregon]], the agency responsible for the implementation of the Health Care Exchange in compliance of the [[Affordable Care Act]].  Previously, Pettit was the first CIO for the State of Oklahoma, serving from April 2010 until January 2014.\n\nPettit was appointed to his position by [[Governor of Oregon|Governor]] [[John Kitzhaber]] on January 6, 2014.\n\n==Biography==\nPettit earned his bachelor's degree from the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Parkside]] and received a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Loyola University of Chicago]]. In 2014, he completed his [[Ph.D.]] in Interdisciplinary Information Sciences from the [[University of North Texas]].  Pettit is a member of the [[Beta Gamma Sigma]] International Honor Society.\n\nPettit began his public career in 1998 in [[Denton, Texas]] as the first Chief Technology Officer for the city.  He served in this capacity until October 2008.  He then worked for [[Marsh McLennan]] in the areas of business continuity planning strategy and vision, disaster recovery and business resumption planning. He served in that position until 2009 when he became a consultant for [[Brown University]] where he served as project manager for planning and coordination of Brown's data center.\n\nIn 2010, Governor of Oklahoma [[Brad Henry]] appointed Pettit as the State's first Chief Information Officer. As State CIO, Pettit served as a member of the [[Oklahoma Governor's Cabinet]] and received an annual salary of $160,000. On January 6, 2011, Governor-elect [[Mary Fallin]] announced that she would retain Pettit as State CIO.  Pettit left the State of Oklahoma in January, 2014 to assume the position of CIO for the State of Oregon.  On April 6, 2018 Pettit resigned his position as the State of Oregon CIO.  He served in the administration of Governor [[Kate Brown]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101222194411/http://www.gov.ok.gov/display_article.php?article_id=1368&article_type=1 Gov. Henry names Pettit new CIO], Office of Governor Henry, 3-26-10\n*[http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-structures-ownership/14190318-1.html Henry names Texas name to fill new Chief Information officer post], [[Daily Oklahoman]], 3-27-10\n*[http://www.ok.gov/triton/modules/newsroom/newsroom_article.php?id=223&article_id=232 Governor-elect Mary Fallin to Retain Alex Pettit As Chief Information Officer], Office of Governor Fallin, 1-06-11\n*[http://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/OKOMES/bulletins/984332] Oklahoma CIO Alex Pettit accepts Oregon CIO position\n*[https://blogs.wsj.com/cio/2014/04/01/oregon-health-exchange-cio-is-soon-to-be-ore-gone/] Oregon Health Exchange CIO is soon to be Ore-gone\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101025031400/http://www.nascio.org/aboutNASCIO/profiles/profile.cfm?selectedState=OK State CIO Alex Pettit biography], National Association of State Chief Information Officers\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100920193700/http://www.ok.gov/OSF/State_CIO/State_CIO_-_Biography.html State biography of State CIO Alex Pettit], [[Oklahoma Office of State Finance]]\n*[http://www.oregon.gov/COO/Pages/stateCIO.aspx Oklahoma CIO tapped to lead Oregon IT work]\n*[http://www.oregon.gov/newsroom/Pages/NewsDetail.aspx?newsid=2656 Oregon Chief Information Officer Alex Pettit Announces Resignation], Office of Governor Brown, 4-06-18\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pettit, Alex}}\n[[Category:People from Denton, Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Parkside alumni]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:People from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Chief information officers]]\n[[Category:American chief technology officers]]\n\n\n{{Oklahoma-stub}}\n{{Oregon-gov-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP unsourced|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| name = Alex Pettit\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = April 3, 1966\n| birth_place = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = [[Chief Information Officer]] of the [[State of Oklahoma]]\n| governor = [[Brad Henry]]<br>[[Mary Fallin]]\n| term_start = April 5, 2010\n| term_end = January 3, 2014\n| predecessor = Post created\n| successor = \n| office2 = [[Chief Information Officer]] of the [[Government of Oregon|State of Oregon]]\n| governor2 = [[John Kitzhaber]]<br>[[Kate Brown]]\n| term_start2 = January 4, 2014\n| term_end2 = April 6, 2018\n| predecessor2 =\n| successo2r = \n| occupation = [[Public administration|Public administrator]]\n| party =\n| religion = \n| website =\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Alex Pettit''' is an [[United States|American]] [[public administration]] official who was the [[Chief Information Officer]] for the [[Government of Oregon|State of Oregon]]. As State CIO, Pettit worked in the [[Oregon Department of Administrative Services|Department of Administrative Services]] and was responsible for all information and telecommunication systems for all state agencies.  In March 2014, Pettit was appointed interim CIO for [[Cover Oregon]], the agency responsible for the implementation of the Health Care Exchange in compliance of the [[Affordable Care Act]].  Previously, Pettit was the first CIO for the State of Oklahoma, serving from April 2010 until January 2014.\n\nPettit was appointed to his position by [[Governor of Oregon|Governor]] [[John Kitzhaber]] on January 6, 2014.\n\n==Biography==\nPettit earned his bachelor's degree from the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Parkside]] and received a [[Masters of Business Administration]] from [[Loyola University of Chicago]]. In 2014, he completed his [[Ph.D.]] in Interdisciplinary Information Sciences from the [[University of North Texas]].  Pettit is a member of the [[Beta Gamma Sigma]] International Honor Society.\n\nPettit began his public career in 1998 in [[Denton, Texas]] as the first Chief Technology Officer for the city.  He served in this capacity until October 2008.  He then worked for [[Marsh McLennan]] in the areas of business continuity planning strategy and vision, disaster recovery and business resumption planning. He served in that position until 2009 when he became a consultant for [[Brown University]] where he served as project manager for planning and coordination of Brown's data center.\n\nIn 2010, Governor of Oklahoma [[Brad Henry]] appointed Pettit as the State's first Chief Information Officer. As State CIO, Pettit served as a member of the [[Oklahoma Governor's Cabinet]] and received an annual salary of $160,000. On January 6, 2011, Governor-elect [[Mary Fallin]] announced that she would retain Pettit as State CIO.  Pettit left the State of Oklahoma in January, 2014 to assume the position of CIO for the State of Oregon.  On April 6, 2018 Pettit resigned his position as the State of Oregon CIO.  He served in the administration of Governor [[Kate Brown]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101222194411/http://www.gov.ok.gov/display_article.php?article_id=1368&article_type=1 Gov. Henry names Pettit new CIO], Office of Governor Henry, 3-26-10\n*[http://www.allbusiness.com/company-activities-management/company-structures-ownership/14190318-1.html Henry names Texas name to fill new Chief Information officer post], [[Daily Oklahoman]], 3-27-10\n*[http://www.ok.gov/triton/modules/newsroom/newsroom_article.php?id=223&article_id=232 Governor-elect Mary Fallin to Retain Alex Pettit As Chief Information Officer], Office of Governor Fallin, 1-06-11\n*[http://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/OKOMES/bulletins/984332] Oklahoma CIO Alex Pettit accepts Oregon CIO position\n*[https://blogs.wsj.com/cio/2014/04/01/oregon-health-exchange-cio-is-soon-to-be-ore-gone/] Oregon Health Exchange CIO is soon to be Ore-gone\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101025031400/http://www.nascio.org/aboutNASCIO/profiles/profile.cfm?selectedState=OK State CIO Alex Pettit biography], National Association of State Chief Information Officers\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100920193700/http://www.ok.gov/OSF/State_CIO/State_CIO_-_Biography.html State biography of State CIO Alex Pettit], [[Oklahoma Office of State Finance]]\n*[http://www.oregon.gov/COO/Pages/stateCIO.aspx Oklahoma CIO tapped to lead Oregon IT work]\n*[http://www.oregon.gov/newsroom/Pages/NewsDetail.aspx?newsid=2656 Oregon Chief Information Officer Alex Pettit Announces Resignation], Office of Governor Brown, 4-06-18\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pettit, Alex}}\n[[Category:People from Denton, Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Parkside alumni]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:People from Oregon]]\n[[Category:Chief information officers]]\n[[Category:American chief technology officers]]\n\n\n{{Oklahoma-stub}}\n{{Oregon-