{"title_page": "Combs Reservoir", "text_new": "{{short description|English reservoir}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Combs Reservoir\n| image = Combs Reservoir from Castle Naze.jpg\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Derbyshire]]\n| coords = {{coord|53|18|43|N|1|57|11|W|type:waterbody_region:GB|name=Combs Reservoir}}\n| type = [[reservoir]]\n| inflow = Meverill Brook and Pyegreave Brook\n| outflow = [[Randall Carr]] Brook\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = United Kingdom\n| length = {{Convert|1|km|1}}\n| width = {{Convert|0.5|km|1}}\n| area = \n| depth = \n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = \n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Combs Reservoir from Whitehills by Dave Dunford.jpg|thumb|265x265px|Combs Reservoir from Whitehills]]\n'''Combs Reservoir''' is a canal-feeder reservoir in the [[Peak District National Park]], close to [[Combs, Derbyshire|Combs]] village in [[Derbyshire]]. The town of [[Whaley Bridge|Chapel-en-le-Frith]] lies about {{convert|1|km}} east of the reservoir.<ref name=\"OS2\">{{cite map|publisher=Ordnance Survey|title=OL24 White Peak area|at=West sheet|url=|scale=1:25000|series=Explorer}}</ref>\n\nCombs was built in 1797 as the first reservoir to feed the [[Peak Forest Canal]] (which opened in 1800) at [[Whaley Bridge]]. The canal was critical for transporting goods to and from the corn mills, cotton factories, collieries and other local industry, as well as connecting to the [[Ashton Canal]] for the nearby limestone quarries. In 1831 the [[Macclesfield Canal]] was completed, which was connected to the Peak Forest Canal at [[Marple, Greater Manchester|Marple]]. The [[Toddbrook Reservoir]] at Whaley Bridge was built as an additional feeder reservoir and the dam at Combs Reservoir was raised between 1834 and 1840, in order to meet the demand for a greater water supply to the extended canal system. By the 1940s use of these canals for transporting industrial goods had ended. The reservoir is now owned by the [[Canal & River Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/history/CombsHistory.pdf|title=The History of Combs Sailing Club|last=Broadbent|first=Sandy|date=2000|website=Combs Sailing Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buxton]] to [[Manchester]] railway line runs between Combs Reservoir and Combs village to the south and alongside the western shore.<ref name=\"OS2\" />\n\nThe reservoir is overlooked by [[Eccles Pike]] hill from the north and from the south by the [[Iron Age]] promontory hillfort Castle Naze, at the northern end of [[Combs Moss]]. Castle Naze is a protected [[Scheduled monument|Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1009294|desc=Promontory fort on Combs Edge, Chapel-en-le-Frith|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Reservoir is a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI). It is particularly important for its 'ephemeral [[bryophyte]]' mosses (such as the rare ''Physcomitrium sphaericum'') and [[Marchantiophyta|liverworts]] (''Ricca glauca'' and ''Fossombronia wondraczekii''). The area is a rich habitat for birdlife including the [[great crested grebe]], [[little ringed plover]], [[common snipe|snipe]] and [[Northern lapwing|lapwing]].<ref name=\"SSSI\">{{Cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1000334.pdf|title=Combs Reservoir SSSI|last=|first=|date=20 October 1986|website=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Sailing Club has used the reservoir for sailing training and racing since 1950.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/index.php|title=Combs Sailing Club Online|last=|first=|date=|website=www.combssailingclub.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English reservoir}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Combs Reservoir\n| image = Combs Reservoir from Castle Naze.jpg\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Derbyshire]]\n| coords = {{coord|53|18|43|N|1|57|11|W|type:waterbody_region:GB|name=Combs Reservoir}}\n| type = [[reservoir]]\n| inflow = Meverill Brook and Pyegreave Brook\n| outflow = [[Randall Carr]] Brook\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = United Kingdom\n| length = {{Convert|1|km|1}}\n| width = {{Convert|0.5|km|1}}\n| area = \n| depth = \n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = \n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Combs Reservoir from Whitehills by Dave Dunford.jpg|thumb|265x265px|Combs Reservoir from Whitehills]]\n'''Combs Reservoir''' is a canal-feeder reservoir in the [[Peak District National Park]], close to [[Combs, Derbyshire|Combs]] village in [[Derbyshire]]. The town of [[Whaley Bridge|Chapel-en-le-Frith]] lies about {{convert|1|km}} east of the reservoir.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nCombs was built in 1797 as the first reservoir to feed the [[Peak Forest Canal]] (which opened in 1800) at [[Whaley Bridge]]. The canal was critical for transporting goods to and from the corn mills, cotton factories, collieries and other local industry, as well as connecting to the [[Ashton Canal]] for the nearby limestone quarries. In 1831 the [[Macclesfield Canal]] was completed, which was connected to the Peak Forest Canal at [[Marple, Greater Manchester|Marple]]. The [[Toddbrook Reservoir]] at Whaley Bridge was built as an additional feeder reservoir and the dam at Combs Reservoir was raised between 1834 and 1840, in order to meet the demand for a greater water supply to the extended canal system. By the 1940s use of these canals for transporting industrial goods had ended. The reservoir is now owned by the [[Canal & River Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/history/CombsHistory.pdf|title=The History of Combs Sailing Club|last=Broadbent|first=Sandy|date=2000|website=Combs Sailing Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buxton]] to [[Manchester]] railway line runs between Combs Reservoir and Combs village to the south and alongside the western shore.<ref name=\"OS\" />\n\nThe reservoir is overlooked by [[Eccles Pike]] hill from the north and from the south by the [[Iron Age]] promontory hillfort Castle Naze, at the northern end of [[Combs Moss]]. Castle Naze is a protected [[Scheduled monument|Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1009294|desc=Promontory fort on Combs Edge, Chapel-en-le-Frith|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Reservoir is a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI). It is particularly important for its 'ephemeral [[bryophyte]]' mosses (such as the rare ''Physcomitrium sphaericum'') and [[Marchantiophyta|liverworts]] (''Ricca glauca'' and ''Fossombronia wondraczekii''). The area is a rich habitat for birdlife including the [[great crested grebe]], [[little ringed plover]], [[common snipe|snipe]] and [[Northern lapwing|lapwing]].<ref name=\"SSSI\">{{Cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1000334.pdf|title=Combs Reservoir SSSI|last=|first=|date=20 October 1986|website=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Sailing Club has used the reservoir for sailing training and racing since 1950.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/index.php|title=Combs Sailing Club Online|last=|first=|date=|website=www.combssailingclub.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "OS Map citation using Cite Map template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combs_Reservoir"}
{"title_page": "Suphachai Chearavanont", "text_new": "{{COI|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Suphachai Chearavanont\n| image              = file:01 \u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e28\u0e38\u0e20\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22_edit (2).jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Thai people|Thai]]\n| occupation         = CEO, Charoen Pokphand Group Co., Ltd., chairman of board, True Corporation, PLC.\n| alma_mater         = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n}}\n\n'''Suphachai Chearavanont''' ({{lang-th|\u0e28\u0e38\u0e20\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e08\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e27\u0e19\u0e19\u0e17\u0e4c}}, {{RTGS|''Suphachai Chiarawanon''}}; {{lang-zh|\u8b1d\u6995\u4ec1}}; 24 March 1967) is CEO of [[Charoen Pokphand|C.P. Group]] and Chairman of [[True Corporation]].<ref name=\"NN\"/><ref name=\"XX\" /><ref name=\"SS\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1200329/supachai-rises-at-true#cxrecs_s\u00a0\"Supachai rises at True\"], ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (February 18 , 2017)</ref><ref name=\"TT\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1203909/chairman-vows-to-keep-truevisions-in-operation\u00a0\"Chairman vows to keep TrueVisions in operation\"], Srisamorn Phoosuphanusorn, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (February 24 , 2017)</ref><ref name=\"UU\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1788839/cp-chief-outlines-quick-win-strategy\u00a0\"CP chief outlines 'quick win' strategy\"], Komsan Tortermvasana, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (November 7 , 2019)</ref><ref name=\"VV\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1002821/suphachai-counts-down-to-leading-cp\u00a0\"Suphachai\u00a0counts down to leading CP\"], Srisamorn Phoosuphanusorn, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (June 6 , 2016)</ref><ref name=\"WW\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1695432/suphachai-replacing-dhanin-as-true-chair\u00a0\"Suphachai\u00a0replacing Dhanin as True chair\"], ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (June 15 , 2019)</ref><ref name=\"YY\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1183461/true-boss-to-become-cp-chief-in-conglomerate-reshuffle\u00a0\"True boss to become CP chief in conglomerate reshuffle\"], Komsan Tortermvasana, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (January 20, 2017)</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the Thai Government's Independent Committee for Educational Reform appointed by [[Thai Prime Minister]] [[Prayut Chan-o-cha]]. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nSuphachai Chearavanont was born on March 24, 1967.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} \n* 2018 : Honorary Doctorate Degree in Business Administration from [[Khon Kaen University]]\n* 2018 : Honorary Doctorate Degree in Marketing from Rajamangala Institute of Technology Isan\n* 2016 : Honorary Doctorate Degree in Mass Communications from [[Ramkhamhaeng University]] \n\n==Early career==\n\nWhile in the [[United States]] after graduating, Chearavanont was an intern at a petrochemical factory in [[Houston, Texas]]. On his return to Thailand he gained work experience at Siam Makro, a company in which C.P. Group was then a shareholder. He also gained financial experience by working with Soltext Federal Credit Union in the US and Vinylthai, one of Thailand's leading petrochemical companies. He joined TelecomAsia Corporation, Thailand's largest telecommunication company, in 1992 and worked his way up from a Senior Officer to senior management where his positions included chief operations and planning officer, executive vice-president for business, and senior vice-president for planning, project coordination and support.<ref name = TrueDream>Pattanapan Wongpan and Disanee Nakcharoen., Suphachai Chearavanont: Dream Catcher CEO Making of True.{{Dead link|date=April 2013}}{{Dead link|date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe also served as chief operations officer of UTV Cable Television and founded a number of subsidiaries for the [[True Corporation|TelecomAsia Group]], such as Asia Wireless Communication Company Limited, a PCT (Person Communication Telephone) operator; Asia Infonet Company Limited, which operates internet businesses; Asia Multimedia Company Limited, a broadband operator; and Wire and Wireless Company Limited, a construction and distribution business.\n\n==Career==\n\n===True Corporation===\n\n====Starting the telecommunications business====\n\nThe years 1992 to 1996 were a boom era for the Thai telecommunications industry. The government had granted concessions to allow the private sector to invest in fixed-line, mobile and other new telecom services. Many private companies received both domestic and overseas loans to invest in the Thai telecom business. C.P. Group was one of the few privately owned Thai companies with the potential to operate such a business and it was invited to compete with foreign companies in a bid for concessions, which C.P. Group won.<ref name = RightMan>Supattha Sukchoo and Napaporn Chaikhankaew, May 3, 2012.  [http://www.gotomanager.com/news/printnews.aspx?id=94068 Print News]</ref>\n\nChearvanont first worked in the company's operations room and gradually gained knowledge about the fixed-line business where he worked as the senior officer for the president's office. He was promoted until he was responsible for managing network rollout, being responsible for the overview of the business and for leading the installation of a network of 2.6 million fixed-line phones. The network was successfully installed within two years.<ref name=\"TrueDream\"/>\n \nAs with most Thai companies, TelecomAsia was affected by the [[1997 Asian financial crisis]] which saw the Thai Baht collapse from 25 Baht/USD to 55 Baht/USD. The company's debt almost doubled to around 90 billion Baht and it was unable to repay its obligations within the due date and had to negotiate delayed repayment and enter a restructuring process.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nChearvanont explained to creditors that the fixed-line business was still growing and that evolving technology would lead to the development of data services which TelecomAsia would be able to commercially exploit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Suphachai Chearavanont l Bio l Cambridge Institute for Family Enterprise - 17 Next Generation Leaders of 2017 |url=https://cfeg.com/nextgenleaders2017/bio/suphachai-chearavanont.html |accessdate=2018-12-17}}</ref>  The creditors approved TelecomAsia's restructured debt-repayment program. Once the economy had recovered from the Asian financial crisis, the company developed a diverse range of new marketing activities which helped improve its financial position and revenue base. In 1999, Chearvanont was promoted to the position of President and CEO.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====Recovery and consolidation====\n\nIn 2003, Chearvanont and then TelecomAsia invested heavily in building up the country's third national wireless carrier, over a decade behind competitors. TA Orange grew rapidly during its first years under heavy and innovative marketing campaign. Chearvanont and TA Orange soon ran into trouble when [[France Telecom]] acquired Orange (UK) and France Telecom refused to increase capital and funding into the TA Orange joint venture. TA Orange, thus, was unable to keep up with competitor investments and expand its network fast enough. In 2005, TelecomAsia struck a deal to buy out France Telecom's stake in TA Orange for 1 Thai baht. Upon the buyback of TA Orange, TelecomAsia transformed itself into \"True Corporation\". Chearvanont soon also took a controlling stake in UBC, then the country's leading independent pay TV provider, and transformed it into True Visions.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nUnder Chearvanont's leadership, TelecomAsia transformed from a fixed-line phone provider to Thailand's leading telecommunications conglomerate, being Thailand's largest internet service provider, cable TV and pay TV provider, and the country's third-largest wireless carrier with some 24 million subscribers. In June 2015, Chearvanont was elected President of The Telecommunications Association of Thailand under The Royal Patronage.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Charoen Pokphand Group===\n\nOn January 9, 2017, Chearavanont was appointed CEO with Soopakij Chearavanont appointed as Chairman and [[Dhanin Chearavanont]] progressing towards the position of Senior Chairman of the Charoen Pokphand Group.<ref name=\"XX\">{{Citation |last=Ono |first=Yukako |date=January 17, 2017 |title=CP Group's Dhanin elevates 2 sons to chairman, CEO |publisher=[[Nikkei Asian Review]] |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/CP-Group-s-Dhanin-elevates-2-sons-to-chairman-CEO |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Chearavanont was honored by [[Muhammad Yunus]], [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Laureate, to give a keynote speech at the closing ceremony of \u20182019 Social Business Day\u2019, marking the ninth time the event was organized and the first of its kind in Thailand. The aim of the event was to demonstrate how the Thai private sector could drive and utilize the \u2018Social Business\u2019 model to help solve challenging social issues.<ref>{{Citation|year=2019 |title=Social Business Day 2019 |publisher=CP Group |url=http://www.cpgroupglobal.com/th/News/nDetail/articleid/95 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |year=2019 |title=Social Business Day |publisher=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dxwv1Jm10rI |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Chearavanont, as Co-Chair of the [[World Economic Forum]] - Dalian in China, shared views and experiences during sessions titled \u2018Conversations on Leadership 4.0\u2019 and \u2018Leadership 4.0: Success in the New Era of Globalization\u2019.<ref>https://www.weforum.org/events/annual-meeting-of-the-new-champions-2019/sessions/a0W0X00000FuPS2UAN</ref><ref>https://www.weforum.org/events/annual-meeting-of-the-new-champions-2019/sessions/the-quest-for-leadership-4-0</ref> Also in July  2019, Chearavanont gave the opening speech on True Digital Academy\u2019s initiation workshop \u201cData for Leader.\"<ref>{{Citation |year=2019 |title=12072019 True Digital Academy - Chairman\u2019s opening speech |publisher=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8URd8MnPLgg |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe has published articles on building responsible supply chains,<ref name=nation>{{Citation |last=Chearavanont |first=Suphachai |date=July 10, 2019 |title=How to create responsible supply chains in the age of globalization 4.0 |publisher= |url=https://www.nationthailand.com/opinion/30372649 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref> and among other projects, he formed a C.P. Group program to limit deforestation in Thailand by helping farmers replace maize with other crops.<ref name=bp>{{Citation |last=Charoensuthipan| first=Penchan|title=CP stung by bald mountain accusations| url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/912092/cp-stung-by-bald-mountain-accusations|accessdate=January 19, 2020|publisher=[[Bangkok Post]]|date=2016-03-28}}</ref> In September 2019, Chearavanont attended a meeting with leaders of the [[United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO). Furthermore, he also met with Paul Polman and  Lise Kingo, CEO and Executive Director of the [[UN Global Compact]], to discuss the development of the Global Compact Network Thailand.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn October 2019 Chearavanont was selected Chairman of the Digital Council of Thailand. He gave the speech \u201cBring a digital future to everyone: making changes to remap Thailand in the digital world\u201d at the \u201cDigital Thailand Big Bang 2019: Asean Connectivity\u201d.<ref name=\"NN\">{{Citation |date=October 29, 2019 |title=Digital Economy Council chairman seeks to transform country into digital hub |publisher=[[The Nation]] |url=https://www.nationthailand.com/news/30377848 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |year= 2019|title=Digital Big Bang 2019 |publisher=CPG |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AhvZDOsBSUs |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n \n==Work experience==\n* 2017\u2013Present: CEO, Charoen Pokphand Group Co., Ltd.\n* 2015-2016: Vice Chairman, Charoen Pokphand Group\n* Present: Chairman of the Board, True Corporation, PLC.\n* 1999\u2013February 20, 2017: President & CEO, True Corporation Plc.\n* 2006\u2013Present:\tChief Executive Officer, True Visions Plc.\n* 2002\u2013Present: Chief Executive Officer, True Move Co., Ltd.\n* 2011\u2013Present: President & Chief Executive Officer, Real Move Co., Ltd.\n* 2001\u2013Present: Chairman, Pantavanij Co., Ltd.\n* 2000-2005: Chairman, Freewill Solutions Co., Ltd.\n* 1999\u2013Present: Chairman, Wire & Wireless Co., Ltd.\t\t   \t\t\t\t\t\n* 1997: Senior Executive Vice President, TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1996:\t\n**Executive Vice President, Business Operations, TelecomAsia Plc.\n**President, Asia Multimedia Co., Ltd.\n* 1995:\t\n**General Manager, East Region, TelecomAsia Plc.\n**Chief Operating Officer, UTV Cable Network Plc. \n**Managing Director, Wire & Wireless Co., Ltd.\n* 1994: Senior Vice President, Planning and Project Coordination & Support TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1993: Vice President, Operations Room, TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1992: Senior Officer, President's Office, TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1991: 2 years with Vinythai Co., Ltd.\n* 1990: 1 year with Soltex Federal Credit Union, USA\n* 1989: 1 year with Siam Makro Co., Ltd.\n\n==Directorships==\n* [[True Corporation]] Plc\n* [[True Move]] Co., Ltd. \t\t\n* [[TrueVisions]] Plc.\t\n* and other subsidiaries of True Corporation Plc.\t\n* Pantavanij Co., Ltd. \t\t\n* Asia  Freewill  Co., Ltd.\n* CPPC Plc.\n* Freewill Solutions Co., Ltd.\n* C.P. Pokphand Co., Ltd.\n\n==Other memberships and positions==\n* Present : The Chairman of the Digital Council of Thailand\n* 2018\u2013Present : President of  Global Compact Network - Thailand  \n* 2017\u2013Present: Advisor to the University Council of the Thai Chamber of Commerce University\n* 2017\u2013Present: President of The Thai Federation of ICT Technology Association\n* 2017\u2013Present: A member of the Thai Government's Independent Committee for Educational Reform\n* 2017\u2013Present: Advisor to the Thai Chamber of Commerce \n* 2016\u2013Present: Chair of the Preparatory Committee for the United Nations Global Compact Network Thailand\n* 2015\u2013Present: Head of Private Sector Team of Public Private Partnership in Education and Leadership Development\n* 2015\u2013present: Counselor and Advisory Board Member for [[One Young World]] Summit 2015\n* 2015\u2013present: President of The Telecommunications Association of Thailand under The Royal Patronage\n* 2010\u20132017:\tAdvisor to Executive Chairman of Rajaprajanugroh Foundation\n* 2010\u2013Present: Committee of Ramathibodi Foundation\n* 2010\u20132016:    Committee of Bangkok Art and Culture Center\n* 2009\u20132017:    Board Member of Board of Trustees, Bangkok University\n* 2008\u2013Present: Member of Management Committee on Nation-Wide Strategic Approach Eye Provisioning Project\n* 2006\u2013Present: Chairman of the Sub Committee for Fund Raising, Thai Red Cross Eye Bank\n* 2006\u2013Present: Member of the Thai Red Cross Eye bank Committee\n* 1999\u2013Present: Director & Advisor of the Telecommunications Association of Thailand under the Royal Patronage (TCT)\n* 2005-2007: Member of the Listed Companies Association (LCA)\n* 1996 to 2000: Advisor to the President of the House of Representatives (Wan Mohamad Noor Matha)\n\n==Honors and awards==\nIn 2015 Chearavanont was presented with the \u201c2015 [[Frost & Sullivan]] Asia Pacific Telecom CEO of the Year\u201d award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frost & Sullivan Award 2015|url=http://www3.truecorp.co.th/the_asia_pacific_ict_awards/index_en.html}}</ref> In March 2019, Chearavanont was presented with the \u201cThai Venerable People Award 2019\u201d in the category of Outstanding Religion Support, organized by Asia Media Thailand Communication Association and Thai Society Support Network Council.<ref>https://www.newsplus.co.th/162747</ref>  In June 2019, Chearavanont was presented with the 6th \u201cThai People Role Model Award 2019\u201d in the category of Outstanding Mass Communication, organized by The Radio, Television and Newspaper Program Producer Assembly of Thailand.<ref>{{Citation|year=2019 |title= Article|publisher=SiamRath |url=https://siamrath.co.th/n/82998{ |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref> Furthermore, Chearavanont was presented with  The Gold Telly Awards 2019 in the Religion TV Program Category from [[New York City|New York]] for the TV \u201cTrue Little Monk : A Wisdom Training Programme for Novices\u201d.<ref>{{Citation |year=2019 |title=Gold Telly Award 2019 |publisher=Pracha Chat |url=https://www.prachachat.net/general/news-344408 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther notable awards and accolades include: \n* 2013 : Asia Brand Management Innovation Personality Award from the 8th Asia Brand Award held in Hong Kong\n* 2012 : Thailand's Best Human Resources Practitioner Award 2012 under the category of CEO and HR professionals from Human Resources Institute, [[Thammasat University]]\n* 2011 : Role Model 2011 by 360\u0e4d ''Manager Magazine''\n* 2008 : Top 10 Role Model 2008 by the readers of Manager Magazine.\n* 2006 : Telecom Man of the Year from the Ministry of Information and Communication Technology of Thailand\n* 2006 : Priew Award (Business & Marketing)\u201d from ''Priew Magazine''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cpgroupglobal.com/about/boards Biography at C.P. Group]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chearavanont, Suphachai}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Thai businesspeople|Suphachai Chearavanont]]\n[[Category:People from Bangkok|Suphachai Chearavanont]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Assumption College (Thailand)|Suphachai Chearavanont]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Management alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Suphachai Chearavanont\n| image              = file:01 \u0e04\u0e38\u0e13\u0e28\u0e38\u0e20\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22_edit (2).jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Thai people|Thai]]\n| occupation         = CEO, Charoen Pokphand Group Co., Ltd., chairman of board, True Corporation, PLC.\n| alma_mater         = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n}}\n\n'''Suphachai Chearavanont''' ({{lang-th|\u0e28\u0e38\u0e20\u0e0a\u0e31\u0e22 \u0e40\u0e08\u0e35\u0e22\u0e23\u0e27\u0e19\u0e19\u0e17\u0e4c}}, {{RTGS|''Suphachai Chiarawanon''}}; {{lang-zh|\u8b1d\u6995\u4ec1}}; 24 March 1967) is CEO of [[Charoen Pokphand|C.P. Group]] and Chairman of [[True Corporation]].<ref name=\"NN\"/><ref name=\"XX/><ref name=\"SS\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1200329/supachai-rises-at-true#cxrecs_s\u00a0\"Supachai rises at True\"], ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (February 18 , 2017)</ref><ref name=\"TT\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1203909/chairman-vows-to-keep-truevisions-in-operation\u00a0\"Chairman vows to keep TrueVisions in operation\"], Srisamorn Phoosuphanusorn, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (February 24 , 2017)</ref><ref name=\"UU\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1788839/cp-chief-outlines-quick-win-strategy\u00a0\"CP chief outlines 'quick win' strategy\"], Komsan Tortermvasana, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (November 7 , 2019)</ref><ref name=\"VV\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1002821/suphachai-counts-down-to-leading-cp\u00a0\"Suphachai\u00a0counts down to leading CP\"], Srisamorn Phoosuphanusorn, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (June 6 , 2016)</ref><ref name=\"WW\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1695432/suphachai-replacing-dhanin-as-true-chair\u00a0\"Suphachai\u00a0replacing Dhanin as True chair\"], ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (June 15 , 2019)</ref><ref name=\"YY\">[https://www.bangkokpost.com/business/1183461/true-boss-to-become-cp-chief-in-conglomerate-reshuffle\u00a0\"True boss to become CP chief in conglomerate reshuffle\"], Komsan Tortermvasana, ''[[Bangkok Post]]'' (January 20, 2017)</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the Thai Government's Independent Committee for Educational Reform appointed by [[Thai Prime Minister]] [[Prayut Chan-o-cha]]. \n\n== Early life and education ==\nSuphachai Chearavanont was born on March 24, 1967.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} \n* 2018 : Honorary Doctorate Degree in Business Administration from [[Khon Kaen University]]\n* 2018 : Honorary Doctorate Degree in Marketing from Rajamangala Institute of Technology Isan\n* 2016 : Honorary Doctorate Degree in Mass Communications from [[Ramkhamhaeng University]] \n\n==Early career==\n\nWhile in the [[United States]] after graduating, Chearavanont was an intern at a petrochemical factory in [[Houston, Texas]]. On his return to Thailand he gained work experience at Siam Makro, a company in which C.P. Group was then a shareholder. He also gained financial experience by working with Soltext Federal Credit Union in the US and Vinylthai, one of Thailand's leading petrochemical companies. He joined TelecomAsia Corporation, Thailand's largest telecommunication company, in 1992 and worked his way up from a Senior Officer to senior management where his positions included chief operations and planning officer, executive vice-president for business, and senior vice-president for planning, project coordination and support.<ref name = TrueDream>Pattanapan Wongpan and Disanee Nakcharoen., Suphachai Chearavanont: Dream Catcher CEO Making of True.{{Dead link|date=April 2013}}{{Dead link|date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe also served as chief operations officer of UTV Cable Television and founded a number of subsidiaries for the [[True Corporation|TelecomAsia Group]], such as Asia Wireless Communication Company Limited, a PCT (Person Communication Telephone) operator; Asia Infonet Company Limited, which operates internet businesses; Asia Multimedia Company Limited, a broadband operator; and Wire and Wireless Company Limited, a construction and distribution business.\n\n==Career==\n\n===True Corporation===\n\n====Starting the telecommunications business====\n\nThe years 1992 to 1996 were a boom era for the Thai telecommunications industry. The government had granted concessions to allow the private sector to invest in fixed-line, mobile and other new telecom services. Many private companies received both domestic and overseas loans to invest in the Thai telecom business. C.P. Group was one of the few privately owned Thai companies with the potential to operate such a business and it was invited to compete with foreign companies in a bid for concessions, which C.P. Group won.<ref name = RightMan>Supattha Sukchoo and Napaporn Chaikhankaew, May 3, 2012.  [http://www.gotomanager.com/news/printnews.aspx?id=94068 Print News]</ref>\n\nChearvanont first worked in the company's operations room and gradually gained knowledge about the fixed-line business where he worked as the senior officer for the president's office. He was promoted until he was responsible for managing network rollout, being responsible for the overview of the business and for leading the installation of a network of 2.6 million fixed-line phones. The network was successfully installed within two years.<ref name=\"TrueDream\"/>\n \nAs with most Thai companies, TelecomAsia was affected by the [[1997 Asian financial crisis]] which saw the Thai Baht collapse from 25 Baht/USD to 55 Baht/USD. The company's debt almost doubled to around 90 billion Baht and it was unable to repay its obligations within the due date and had to negotiate delayed repayment and enter a restructuring process.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nChearvanont explained to creditors that the fixed-line business was still growing and that evolving technology would lead to the development of data services which TelecomAsia would be able to commercially exploit.<ref>{{cite web|title=Suphachai Chearavanont l Bio l Cambridge Institute for Family Enterprise - 17 Next Generation Leaders of 2017 |url=https://cfeg.com/nextgenleaders2017/bio/suphachai-chearavanont.html |accessdate=2018-12-17}}</ref>  The creditors approved TelecomAsia's restructured debt-repayment program. Once the economy had recovered from the Asian financial crisis, the company developed a diverse range of new marketing activities which helped improve its financial position and revenue base. In 1999, Chearvanont was promoted to the position of President and CEO.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n====Recovery and consolidation====\n\nIn 2003, Chearvanont and then TelecomAsia invested heavily in building up the country's third national wireless carrier, over a decade behind competitors. TA Orange grew rapidly during its first years under heavy and innovative marketing campaign. Chearvanont and TA Orange soon ran into trouble when [[France Telecom]] acquired Orange (UK) and France Telecom refused to increase capital and funding into the TA Orange joint venture. TA Orange, thus, was unable to keep up with competitor investments and expand its network fast enough. In 2005, TelecomAsia struck a deal to buy out France Telecom's stake in TA Orange for 1 Thai baht. Upon the buyback of TA Orange, TelecomAsia transformed itself into \"True Corporation\". Chearvanont soon also took a controlling stake in UBC, then the country's leading independent pay TV provider, and transformed it into True Visions.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nUnder Chearvanont's leadership, TelecomAsia transformed from a fixed-line phone provider to Thailand's leading telecommunications conglomerate, being Thailand's largest internet service provider, cable TV and pay TV provider, and the country's third-largest wireless carrier with some 24 million subscribers. In June 2015, Chearvanont was elected President of The Telecommunications Association of Thailand under The Royal Patronage.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Charoen Pokphand Group===\n\nOn January 9, 2017, Chearavanont was appointed CEO with Soopakij Chearavanont appointed as Chairman and [[Dhanin Chearavanont]] progressing towards the position of Senior Chairman of the Charoen Pokphand Group.<ref name=\"XX>{{Citation |last=Ono |first=Yukako |date=January 17, 2017 |title=CP Group's Dhanin elevates 2 sons to chairman, CEO |publisher=[[Nikkei Asian Review]] |url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/CP-Group-s-Dhanin-elevates-2-sons-to-chairman-CEO |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Chearavanont was honored by [[Muhammad Yunus]], [[Nobel Peace Prize]] Laureate, to give a keynote speech at the closing ceremony of \u20182019 Social Business Day\u2019, marking the ninth time the event was organized and the first of its kind in Thailand. The aim of the event was to demonstrate how the Thai private sector could drive and utilize the \u2018Social Business\u2019 model to help solve challenging social issues.<ref>{{Citation|year=2019 |title=Social Business Day 2019 |publisher=CP Group |url=http://www.cpgroupglobal.com/th/News/nDetail/articleid/95 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |year=2019 |title=Social Business Day |publisher=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dxwv1Jm10rI |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Chearavanont, as Co-Chair of the [[World Economic Forum]] - Dalian in China, shared views and experiences during sessions titled \u2018Conversations on Leadership 4.0\u2019 and \u2018Leadership 4.0: Success in the New Era of Globalization\u2019.<ref>https://www.weforum.org/events/annual-meeting-of-the-new-champions-2019/sessions/a0W0X00000FuPS2UAN</ref><ref>https://www.weforum.org/events/annual-meeting-of-the-new-champions-2019/sessions/the-quest-for-leadership-4-0</ref> Also in July  2019, Chearavanont gave the opening speech on True Digital Academy\u2019s initiation workshop \u201cData for Leader.\"<ref>{{Citation |year=2019 |title=12072019 True Digital Academy - Chairman\u2019s opening speech |publisher=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8URd8MnPLgg |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe has published articles on building responsible supply chains,<ref name=nation>{{Citation |last=Chearavanont |first=Suphachai |date=July 10, 2019 |title=How to create responsible supply chains in the age of globalization 4.0 |publisher= |url=https://www.nationthailand.com/opinion/30372649 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref> and among other projects, he formed a C.P. Group program to limit deforestation in Thailand by helping farmers replace maize with other crops.<ref name=bp>{{Citation |last=Charoensuthipan| first=Penchan|title=CP stung by bald mountain accusations| url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/business/news/912092/cp-stung-by-bald-mountain-accusations|accessdate=January 19, 2020|publisher=[[Bangkok Post]]|date=2016-03-28}}</ref> In September 2019, Chearavanont attended a meeting with leaders of the [[United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization]] (FAO). Furthermore, he also met with Paul Polman and  Lise Kingo, CEO and Executive Director of the [[UN Global Compact]], to discuss the development of the Global Compact Network Thailand.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn October 2019 Chearavanont was selected Chairman of the Digital Council of Thailand. He gave the speech \u201cBring a digital future to everyone: making changes to remap Thailand in the digital world\u201d at the \u201cDigital Thailand Big Bang 2019: Asean Connectivity\u201d.<ref name=\"NN\">{{Citation |date=October 29, 2019 |title=Digital Economy Council chairman seeks to transform country into digital hub |publisher=[[The Nation]] |url=https://www.nationthailand.com/news/30377848 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation |year= 2019|title=Digital Big Bang 2019 |publisher=CPG |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AhvZDOsBSUs |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n \n==Work experience==\n* 2017\u2013Present: CEO, Charoen Pokphand Group Co., Ltd.\n* 2015-2016: Vice Chairman, Charoen Pokphand Group\n* Present: Chairman of the Board, True Corporation, PLC.\n* 1999\u2013February 20, 2017: President & CEO, True Corporation Plc.\n* 2006\u2013Present:\tChief Executive Officer, True Visions Plc.\n* 2002\u2013Present: Chief Executive Officer, True Move Co., Ltd.\n* 2011\u2013Present: President & Chief Executive Officer, Real Move Co., Ltd.\n* 2001\u2013Present: Chairman, Pantavanij Co., Ltd.\n* 2000-2005: Chairman, Freewill Solutions Co., Ltd.\n* 1999\u2013Present: Chairman, Wire & Wireless Co., Ltd.\t\t   \t\t\t\t\t\n* 1997: Senior Executive Vice President, TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1996:\t\n**Executive Vice President, Business Operations, TelecomAsia Plc.\n**President, Asia Multimedia Co., Ltd.\n* 1995:\t\n**General Manager, East Region, TelecomAsia Plc.\n**Chief Operating Officer, UTV Cable Network Plc. \n**Managing Director, Wire & Wireless Co., Ltd.\n* 1994: Senior Vice President, Planning and Project Coordination & Support TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1993: Vice President, Operations Room, TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1992: Senior Officer, President's Office, TelecomAsia Plc.\n* 1991: 2 years with Vinythai Co., Ltd.\n* 1990: 1 year with Soltex Federal Credit Union, USA\n* 1989: 1 year with Siam Makro Co., Ltd.\n\n==Directorships==\n* [[True Corporation]] Plc\n* [[True Move]] Co., Ltd. \t\t\n* [[TrueVisions]] Plc.\t\n* and other subsidiaries of True Corporation Plc.\t\n* Pantavanij Co., Ltd. \t\t\n* Asia  Freewill  Co., Ltd.\n* CPPC Plc.\n* Freewill Solutions Co., Ltd.\n* C.P. Pokphand Co., Ltd.\n\n==Other memberships and positions==\n* Present : The Chairman of the Digital Council of Thailand\n* 2018\u2013Present : President of  Global Compact Network - Thailand  \n* 2017\u2013Present: Advisor to the University Council of the Thai Chamber of Commerce University\n* 2017\u2013Present: President of The Thai Federation of ICT Technology Association\n* 2017\u2013Present: A member of the Thai Government's Independent Committee for Educational Reform\n* 2017\u2013Present: Advisor to the Thai Chamber of Commerce \n* 2016\u2013Present: Chair of the Preparatory Committee for the United Nations Global Compact Network Thailand\n* 2015\u2013Present: Head of Private Sector Team of Public Private Partnership in Education and Leadership Development\n* 2015\u2013present: Counselor and Advisory Board Member for [[One Young World]] Summit 2015\n* 2015\u2013present: President of The Telecommunications Association of Thailand under The Royal Patronage\n* 2010\u20132017:\tAdvisor to Executive Chairman of Rajaprajanugroh Foundation\n* 2010\u2013Present: Committee of Ramathibodi Foundation\n* 2010\u20132016:    Committee of Bangkok Art and Culture Center\n* 2009\u20132017:    Board Member of Board of Trustees, Bangkok University\n* 2008\u2013Present: Member of Management Committee on Nation-Wide Strategic Approach Eye Provisioning Project\n* 2006\u2013Present: Chairman of the Sub Committee for Fund Raising, Thai Red Cross Eye Bank\n* 2006\u2013Present: Member of the Thai Red Cross Eye bank Committee\n* 1999\u2013Present: Director & Advisor of the Telecommunications Association of Thailand under the Royal Patronage (TCT)\n* 2005-2007: Member of the Listed Companies Association (LCA)\n* 1996 to 2000: Advisor to the President of the House of Representatives (Wan Mohamad Noor Matha)\n\n==Honors and awards==\nIn 2015 Chearavanont was presented with the \u201c2015 [[Frost & Sullivan]] Asia Pacific Telecom CEO of the Year\u201d award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frost & Sullivan Award 2015|url=http://www3.truecorp.co.th/the_asia_pacific_ict_awards/index_en.html}}</ref> In March 2019, Chearavanont was presented with the \u201cThai Venerable People Award 2019\u201d in the category of Outstanding Religion Support, organized by Asia Media Thailand Communication Association and Thai Society Support Network Council.<ref>https://www.newsplus.co.th/162747</ref>  In June 2019, Chearavanont was presented with the 6th \u201cThai People Role Model Award 2019\u201d in the category of Outstanding Mass Communication, organized by The Radio, Television and Newspaper Program Producer Assembly of Thailand.<ref>{{Citation|year=2019 |title= Article|publisher=SiamRath |url=https://siamrath.co.th/n/82998{ |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref> Furthermore, Chearavanont was presented with  The Gold Telly Awards 2019 in the Religion TV Program Category from [[New York City|New York]] for the TV \u201cTrue Little Monk : A Wisdom Training Programme for Novices\u201d.<ref>{{Citation |year=2019 |title=Gold Telly Award 2019 |publisher=Pracha Chat |url=https://www.prachachat.net/general/news-344408 |accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOther notable awards and accolades include: \n* 2013 : Asia Brand Management Innovation Personality Award from the 8th Asia Brand Award held in Hong Kong\n* 2012 : Thailand's Best Human Resources Practitioner Award 2012 under the category of CEO and HR professionals from Human Resources Institute, [[Thammasat University]]\n* 2011 : Role Model 2011 by 360\u0e4d ''Manager Magazine''\n* 2008 : Top 10 Role Model 2008 by the readers of Manager Magazine.\n* 2006 : Telecom Man of the Year from the Ministry of Information and Communication Technology of Thailand\n* 2006 : Priew Award (Business & Marketing)\u201d from ''Priew Magazine''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cpgroupglobal.com/about/boards Biography at C.P. Group]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chearavanont, Suphachai}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Thai businesspeople|Suphachai Chearavanont]]\n[[Category:People from Bangkok|Suphachai Chearavanont]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Assumption College (Thailand)|Suphachai Chearavanont]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Management alumni]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character.)", "u