{"title_page": "Coronavirus pandemic anti-Muslim riots in India", "text_new": "{{short description|Anti-Muslim conflict in India}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title      = Coronavirus pandemic anti-Muslim riots in India\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| map = India states and union territories map.svg\n| map_caption = A map showing the states and union territories of India, including [[Delhi]], [[Bihar]] and [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| location   = India\n| coordinates = \n| target     = [[Muslim]]s<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n| date       = 2020\n| time       = \n| timezone   = \n| type       =  [[Lynching]], [[Harassment]]\n| fatalities = \n| injuries   = \n| perps      = [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]]s <ref name=\"Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus in India: Muslims as scapegoats | website=Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World | url=https://en.qantara.de/content/coronavirus-in-india-muslims-as-scapegoats | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News 2020\">{{cite web | title=Islamophobia concerns after India mosque outbreak | website=BBC News | date=3 April 2020 | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52147260 | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| susperps   = \n| weapons    = \n}}\nThe '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus pandemic]]''' \n\nThis is all fake.'''anti-Muslim riots''' refers to an ongoing series of [[Religious violence|religiously motivated]] riots or [[Lynching|mob attack]]s that are being carried out by the [[Violent extremism|extremist]]s against the [[Muslims]] in India.<ref name=\"Apoorvanand 2020\">{{cite web | author=Apoorvanand | title=How the coronavirus outbreak in India was blamed on Muslims | website=Al Jazeera | date=18 April 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/coronavirus-outbreak-india-blamed-muslims-200418143252362.html | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> The lynching incidents occurred primarily after [[Tablighi Jamaat]] was held responsible by the officials for [[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|spreading covid-19]] in the country.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/world/asia/india-coronavirus-muslims-bigotry.html|title=In India, Coronavirus Fans Religious Hatred|first1=Jeffrey|last1=Gettleman|first2=Kai|last2=Schultz|first3=Suhasini|last3=Raj|date=April 12, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/14/coronavirus-muslims-islamophobia/|title=The Coronavirus Is Empowering Islamophobes \u2014 but Exposing the Idiocy of Islamophobia|first=Mehdi|last=Hasan|date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Mob cases were reported by the [[news media]] after some people related to the missionary were tested positive for [[pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], though infectious disease spread [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide]] with thousands of deaths since it originated in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/28/india-delhi-first-came-the-pogroms-now-theres-coronavirus/|title=In Delhi, First Came the Pogroms. Then Came Coronavirus.|first=Yashraj|last=Sharma}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/covid-19-rumours-linked-to-3-attacks-in-delhi-gurgaon-6350696/|title=COVID-19 rumours linked to 3 attacks in Delhi, Gurgaon|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The pandemic triggered severe [[Strike (attack)|attack]]s on the minorities, leading violence between the adherents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/briefing/coronavirus-india-anti-muslim-attacks.html|title=Anti-Muslim Attacks, Boris Johnson, China's New Cases: Your Monday Briefing|first=Melina|last=Delkic|date=April 12, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/17/technology/17reuters-health-coronavirus-india-muslims-insight.html|title=In Modi's India, Virus Fallout Inflames Divisions Between Muslims and Hindus|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> An Indian novelist and activist [[Arundhati Roy]] termed the [[sectarian violence]] \"approaching to genocide\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/indias-treatment-of-muslims-amid-coronavirus-is-almost-genocidal-activist-arundhati-roy-claims/a-53167812|title=India's treatment of Muslims amid coronavirus is almost 'genocidal,' activist Arundhati Roy claims &#124; DW &#124; 17.04.2020|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref><ref name=\"Desk 2020\">{{cite web | last=Desk | first=Web | title=India should protect rights of Muslims amid COVID-19 crisis: OIC - Pakistan | website=The News International | date=19 April 2020 | url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/646709-india-should-protect-muslim-minoritys-rights-amid-covid-19-crisis-islamophobia-oic | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> It is said that '''#CoronaJihad''' [[hashtag]] has been distributed 300,000 times on [[social media]] amid the violence.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5815264/coronavirus-india-islamophobia-coronajihad/|title=It Was Already Dangerous To Be Muslim in India. Then Came the Coronavirus|website=Time}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSince the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case was detected in India on 30 January 2020, the [[Religious violence in India|religious violence]] sparked among the people from different adherents, especially Hindus accusing [[Minority religion|minorities]] for infecting the citizens of the country, though the [[Government of India]] did not took measures to stop religious activities at the earliest.<ref name=\"RFI 2020\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus pandemic used to stir-up anti-Muslim prejeudice in India | website=RFI | date=13 April 2020 | url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/international/20200413-coronavirus-pandemic-used-to-stir-up-anti-muslim-prejeudice-in-india | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> People argued that [[Media of India|Indian news media]] didn't played significantly to stop [[victimisation]] of the Muslims that led some people of the minorities to commit suicide while several others were harassed or lynched at different places.<ref name=\"voa\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/coronavirus-spread-india-sparks-intolerance-toward-minority-muslims|title=Coronavirus Spread in India Sparks Intolerance Toward Minority Muslims &#124; Voice of America - English|website=www.voanews.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.thewire.in/article/communalism/coronavirus-anti-muslim-propaganda-india|title=The Coronavirus Has Morphed Into an Anti-Muslim Virus|website=The Wire}}</ref> Tablighi Jamaat, a Muslim missionary held several [[Ijtema|congregation]]s in the country, claiming in rise of coronavirus cases before [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown was imposed]] in the country.<ref name=\"Beydoun 2020\">{{cite web | last=Beydoun | first=Khaled A. | title=Between virus and violence: The horror of being Muslim in India | website=alaraby | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://english.alaraby.co.uk/english/comment/2020/4/17/between-virus-and-violence-being-muslim-in-india | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> It is said that [[Hindus]] were also actively involved in organising religious debates.<ref name=\"voa\"/>\n\nSome Hindus, including a teenager was also lynched by the mob attackers over not conducted [[COVID-19 testing]] of his two coworkers.<ref name=\"Raj 2020\">{{cite web | last=Raj | first=Dev | title=Teenager lynched for virus alert | website=Telegraph India | date=1 April 2020 | url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/bihar-teenager-lynched-for-coronavirus-alert/cid/1760987 | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Withnall 2020\">{{cite web | last=Withnall | first=Adam | title=Man in India lynched after reporting migrant workers to authorities over coronavirus fears | website=The Independent | date=31 March 2020 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/india-coronavirus-migrant-lynching-madhaul-bihar-quarantine-a9438186.html | language=ca | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Social media controversies==\nThe political leaders, including 25 members of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] termed the islamic conference or congregation \"#coronaJihad\", \"#CoronaTerrorism\" and \"#CoronaBombsTablighi\" using the hashtags that were subsequently circulated by the [[internet users]] across the social media, including Twitter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/13/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-targeting-muslims-spread-in-india|title=Coronavirus conspiracy theories targeting Muslims spread in India|first=Hannah Ellis-Petersen Shaikh Azizur Rahman in|last=Kolkata|newspaper=The Guardian|date=April 13, 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> An Indian politician and former wrestler [[Babita Phogat]] wrote on tweet stating that \"Muslims are bigger problem than even the virus\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52320900|title=India stars under fire for 'anti-Muslim' tweets|work=BBC News|date=April 17, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> Her tweet was later criticised by the several people using \"#SupendBabitaPhogat\" [[Twitter]] hashtag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/babita-phogat-faces-backlash-over-controversial-tweets-on-tablighi-jamaat-1668008-2020-04-17|title=Babita Phogat faces backlash over controversial tweets on Tablighi Jamaat|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiApril 17|first2=2020UPDATED|last2=April 17|first3=2020 15:18|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> The UAE's [[royal family]] member [[Hend Faisal Al Qassemi]] criticised the anti-Muslim tweets posted by an Indian politician [[Deendayal Upadhyaya]] who allegedly made statements against attendees of congregation held in the country during COVID-19 outbreak.<ref name=\"News18 2020\">{{cite web | title='You'll be Made to Leave': UAE Princess Slams Indian Man for Islamophobic Tweet on Tablighi Jamaat | website=News18 | date=18 April 2020 | url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/youll-be-made-to-leave-uae-princess-slams-indian-man-for-islamophobic-tweet-on-tablighi-jamaat-2582657.html | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Safoora Safoora Safoora 2020\">{{cite web | title=UAE Princess takes a strong stand against racist comment | website=The Siasat Daily | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://www.siasat.com/uae-princess-takes-strong-stand-against-racist-comment-1875200/ | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Some Indian employees working with Dubai-based private companies suffered [[termination of employment]] for allegedly sharing coronavirus violence-related posts on social media.<ref name=\"PTI 2020\">{{cite web | author=PTI | title=Another Indian expat in UAE sacked over Islamophobic post | website=The Hindu | date=13 April 2020 | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/another-indian-expat-in-uae-sacked-for-islamophobic-post/article31328980.ece | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n[[Category:Lynching deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Hinduism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Hinduism-motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India]]\n[[Category:Murder in India]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020s murders in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Anti-Muslim conflict in India}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title      = Coronavirus pandemic anti-Muslim riots in India\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| map = India states and union territories map.svg\n| map_caption = A map showing the states and union territories of India, including [[Delhi]], [[Bihar]] and [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| location   = India\n| coordinates = \n| target     = [[Muslim]]s<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n| date       = 2020\n| time       = \n| timezone   = \n| type       =  [[Lynching]], [[Harassment]]\n| fatalities = \n| injuries   = \n| perps      = [[Hindu nationalism|Hindu nationalist]]s <ref name=\"Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus in India: Muslims as scapegoats | website=Qantara.de - Dialogue with the Islamic World | url=https://en.qantara.de/content/coronavirus-in-india-muslims-as-scapegoats | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News 2020\">{{cite web | title=Islamophobia concerns after India mosque outbreak | website=BBC News | date=3 April 2020 | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52147260 | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n| susperps   = \n| weapons    = \n}}\nThe '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus pandemic]]''' '''anti-Muslim riots''' refers to an ongoing series of [[Religious violence|religiously motivated]] riots or [[Lynching|mob attack]]s that are being carried out by the [[Violent extremism|extremist]]s against the [[Muslims]] in India.<ref name=\"Apoorvanand 2020\">{{cite web | author=Apoorvanand | title=How the coronavirus outbreak in India was blamed on Muslims | website=Al Jazeera | date=18 April 2020 | url=https://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/opinion/coronavirus-outbreak-india-blamed-muslims-200418143252362.html | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> The lynching incidents occurred primarily after [[Tablighi Jamaat]] was held responsible by the officials for [[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|spreading covid-19]] in the country.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/world/asia/india-coronavirus-muslims-bigotry.html|title=In India, Coronavirus Fans Religious Hatred|first1=Jeffrey|last1=Gettleman|first2=Kai|last2=Schultz|first3=Suhasini|last3=Raj|date=April 12, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/14/coronavirus-muslims-islamophobia/|title=The Coronavirus Is Empowering Islamophobes \u2014 but Exposing the Idiocy of Islamophobia|first=Mehdi|last=Hasan|date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Mob cases were reported by the [[news media]] after some people related to the missionary were tested positive for [[pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], though infectious disease spread [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide]] with thousands of deaths since it originated in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/28/india-delhi-first-came-the-pogroms-now-theres-coronavirus/|title=In Delhi, First Came the Pogroms. Then Came Coronavirus.|first=Yashraj|last=Sharma}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/covid-19-rumours-linked-to-3-attacks-in-delhi-gurgaon-6350696/|title=COVID-19 rumours linked to 3 attacks in Delhi, Gurgaon|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The pandemic triggered severe [[Strike (attack)|attack]]s on the minorities, leading violence between the adherents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/briefing/coronavirus-india-anti-muslim-attacks.html|title=Anti-Muslim Attacks, Boris Johnson, China's New Cases: Your Monday Briefing|first=Melina|last=Delkic|date=April 12, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/17/technology/17reuters-health-coronavirus-india-muslims-insight.html|title=In Modi's India, Virus Fallout Inflames Divisions Between Muslims and Hindus|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> An Indian novelist and activist [[Arundhati Roy]] termed the [[sectarian violence]] \"approaching to genocide\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/indias-treatment-of-muslims-amid-coronavirus-is-almost-genocidal-activist-arundhati-roy-claims/a-53167812|title=India's treatment of Muslims amid coronavirus is almost 'genocidal,' activist Arundhati Roy claims &#124; DW &#124; 17.04.2020|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref><ref name=\"Desk 2020\">{{cite web | last=Desk | first=Web | title=India should protect rights of Muslims amid COVID-19 crisis: OIC - Pakistan | website=The News International | date=19 April 2020 | url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/646709-india-should-protect-muslim-minoritys-rights-amid-covid-19-crisis-islamophobia-oic | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> It is said that '''#CoronaJihad''' [[hashtag]] has been distributed 300,000 times on [[social media]] amid the violence.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5815264/coronavirus-india-islamophobia-coronajihad/|title=It Was Already Dangerous To Be Muslim in India. Then Came the Coronavirus|website=Time}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSince the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case was detected in India on 30 January 2020, the [[Religious violence in India|religious violence]] sparked among the people from different adherents, especially Hindus accusing [[Minority religion|minorities]] for infecting the citizens of the country, though the [[Government of India]] did not took measures to stop religious activities at the earliest.<ref name=\"RFI 2020\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus pandemic used to stir-up anti-Muslim prejeudice in India | website=RFI | date=13 April 2020 | url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/international/20200413-coronavirus-pandemic-used-to-stir-up-anti-muslim-prejeudice-in-india | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> People argued that [[Media of India|Indian news media]] didn't played significantly to stop [[victimisation]] of the Muslims that led some people of the minorities to commit suicide while several others were harassed or lynched at different places.<ref name=\"voa\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/coronavirus-spread-india-sparks-intolerance-toward-minority-muslims|title=Coronavirus Spread in India Sparks Intolerance Toward Minority Muslims &#124; Voice of America - English|website=www.voanews.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.thewire.in/article/communalism/coronavirus-anti-muslim-propaganda-india|title=The Coronavirus Has Morphed Into an Anti-Muslim Virus|website=The Wire}}</ref> Tablighi Jamaat, a Muslim missionary held several [[Ijtema|congregation]]s in the country, claiming in rise of coronavirus cases before [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown was imposed]] in the country.<ref name=\"Beydoun 2020\">{{cite web | last=Beydoun | first=Khaled A. | title=Between virus and violence: The horror of being Muslim in India | website=alaraby | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://english.alaraby.co.uk/english/comment/2020/4/17/between-virus-and-violence-being-muslim-in-india | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> It is said that [[Hindus]] were also actively involved in organising religious debates.<ref name=\"voa\"/>\n\nSome Hindus, including a teenager was also lynched by the mob attackers over not conducted [[COVID-19 testing]] of his two coworkers.<ref name=\"Raj 2020\">{{cite web | last=Raj | first=Dev | title=Teenager lynched for virus alert | website=Telegraph India | date=1 April 2020 | url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/bihar-teenager-lynched-for-coronavirus-alert/cid/1760987 | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Withnall 2020\">{{cite web | last=Withnall | first=Adam | title=Man in India lynched after reporting migrant workers to authorities over coronavirus fears | website=The Independent | date=31 March 2020 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/india-coronavirus-migrant-lynching-madhaul-bihar-quarantine-a9438186.html | language=ca | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Social media controversies==\nThe political leaders, including 25 members of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] termed the islamic conference or congregation \"#coronaJihad\", \"#CoronaTerrorism\" and \"#CoronaBombsTablighi\" using the hashtags that were subsequently circulated by the [[internet users]] across the social media, including Twitter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/13/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-targeting-muslims-spread-in-india|title=Coronavirus conspiracy theories targeting Muslims spread in India|first=Hannah Ellis-Petersen Shaikh Azizur Rahman in|last=Kolkata|newspaper=The Guardian|date=April 13, 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> An Indian politician and former wrestler [[Babita Phogat]] wrote on tweet stating that \"Muslims are bigger problem than even the virus\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52320900|title=India stars under fire for 'anti-Muslim' tweets|work=BBC News|date=April 17, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> Her tweet was later criticised by the several people using \"#SupendBabitaPhogat\" [[Twitter]] hashtag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/babita-phogat-faces-backlash-over-controversial-tweets-on-tablighi-jamaat-1668008-2020-04-17|title=Babita Phogat faces backlash over controversial tweets on Tablighi Jamaat|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiApril 17|first2=2020UPDATED|last2=April 17|first3=2020 15:18|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> The UAE's [[royal family]] member [[Hend Faisal Al Qassemi]] criticised the anti-Muslim tweets posted by an Indian politician [[Deendayal Upadhyaya]] who allegedly made statements against attendees of congregation held in the country during COVID-19 outbreak.<ref name=\"News18 2020\">{{cite web | title='You'll be Made to Leave': UAE Princess Slams Indian Man for Islamophobic Tweet on Tablighi Jamaat | website=News18 | date=18 April 2020 | url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/youll-be-made-to-leave-uae-princess-slams-indian-man-for-islamophobic-tweet-on-tablighi-jamaat-2582657.html | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Safoora Safoora Safoora 2020\">{{cite web | title=UAE Princess takes a strong stand against racist comment | website=The Siasat Daily | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://www.siasat.com/uae-princess-takes-strong-stand-against-racist-comment-1875200/ | access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> Some Indian employees working with Dubai-based private companies suffered [[termination of employment]] for allegedly sharing coronavirus violence-related posts on social media.<ref name=\"PTI 2020\">{{cite web | author=PTI | title=Another Indian expat in UAE sacked over Islamophobic post | website=The Hindu | date=13 April 2020 | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/another-indian-expat-in-uae-sacked-for-islamophobic-post/article31328980.ece | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n[[Category:Lynching deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Hinduism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Hinduism-motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India]]\n[[Category:Murder in India]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020s murders in India]]\n", "name_user": "103.210.133.142", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_pandemic_anti-Muslim_riots_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Markt (Bruges)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=June 2008}}\n[[File:Belfort Brugge.jpg|thumb | 180 px |upright| Belfry of Bruges]]\n[[File:Brugge Markt1.jpg|thumb | 180 px | Provincial Court]]\n\nThe '''Markt''' (\"Market Square\") of [[Bruges]] is located in the heart of the city and covers an area of about 1 hectare. Some historical highlights around the square include the 12th-century [[Belfry of Bruges|belfry]] and the [[Provinciaal Hof|West Flanders Provincial Court]] (originally the Waterhall, which in 1787 was demolished and replaced by a [[Classicism|classicist]] building that from 1850 served as provincial court and after a fire in 1878 was rebuilt in a neo-Gothic style in 1887. In the center of the market stands the statue of [[Jan Breydel]] and [[Pieter de Coninck]].\n\nIn 1995 the market was completely renovated. Parking in the square was removed and the area became mostly traffic-free, thus being more celebration friendly. The renovated market was reopened in 1996 with a concert by [[Helmut Lotti]].\n\n{{wide image|PanoBrug - IMG 6015 - IMG 6019 - 7525x1974 - CLIN 1.jpg|800px|}}\n\n{{wide image|Postcard - Bruges Cranenburg (Excelsior Series 11, No. 51, Albert Sugg a Gand; ca. 1905).jpg|800px|[[Cranenburg House]] from a postcard, ca. 1905.}}\n\n{{coord|51.2085|N|3.22444|E|type:landmark_region:BE-VWV|display=title}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cranenburg House]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.skylinewebcams.com/webcam/belgique/flandres/bruges/markt.html Live WebCam]\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bruges]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bruges]]\n[[Category:Squares in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=June 2008}}\n[[File:Belfort Brugge.jpg|thumb | 180 px |upright| Belfry of Bruges]]\n[[File:Brugge Markt1.jpg|thumb | 180 px | Provincial Court]]\n{{stub}}\nThe '''Markt''' (\"Market Square\") of [[Bruges]] is located in the heart of the city and covers an area of about 1 hectare. Some historical highlights around the square include the 12th-century [[Belfry of Bruges|belfry]] and the [[Provinciaal Hof|West Flanders Provincial Court]] (originally the Waterhall, which in 1787 was demolished and replaced by a [[Classicism|classicist]] building that from 1850 served as provincial court and after a fire in 1878 was rebuilt in a neo-Gothic style in 1887. In the center of the market stands the statue of [[Jan Breydel]] and [[Pieter de Coninck]].\n\nIn 1995 the market was completely renovated. Parking in the square was removed and the area became mostly traffic-free, thus being more celebration friendly. The renovated market was reopened in 1996 with a concert by [[Helmut Lotti]].\n\n{{wide image|PanoBrug - IMG 6015 - IMG 6019 - 7525x1974 - CLIN 1.jpg|800px|}}\n\n{{wide image|Postcard - Bruges Cranenburg (Excelsior Series 11, No. 51, Albert Sugg a Gand; ca. 1905).jpg|800px|[[Cranenburg House]] from a postcard, ca. 1905.}}\n\n{{coord|51.2085|N|3.22444|E|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cranenburg House]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.skylinewebcams.com/webcam/belgique/flandres/bruges/markt.html Live WebCam]\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bruges]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bruges]]\n[[Category:Squares in Belgium]]\n", "name_user": "Rpyle731", "label": "safe", "comment": "stub sort, fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markt_(Bruges)"}
